      "type": "text",
      "text": "# Customer Segmentation\n\n## Primary Persona: Solo Entrepreneur / One-Person Company\n\nRuns an entire business alone — freelance consultant, agency-of-one, micro-SaaS founder, indie creator. Wears every hat: product, sales, delivery, and marketing. May or may not be technical, but is resourceful and willing to try AI tools. Has no content marketing infrastructure and no budget for agencies. Measured on revenue, inbound leads, and staying visible in their niche.\n\n**Pain points:**\n- **Invisible to AI agents** — When prospects ask ChatGPT \"who's the best [their niche] consultant/tool,\" competitors with better-structured content get cited. They don't know why or how to fix it.\n- **Time poverty** — Every hour on content is an hour not billing clients or building product. Content always loses to revenue-generating work.\n- **No content system** — Publishes in bursts (launch week, a random LinkedIn post) then goes silent for months. No pipeline, no cadence, no compounding.\n- **Can't afford agencies** — $2K/post agencies are out of reach. Freelancers ($500/post) still require briefing and editing that eats the day.\n- **Curious about AI but lost on AEO** — Has heard of AI-generated answers citing brands but hasn't connected the dots that content structure determines whether AI surfaces their business.\n\n**What they'd buy:**\n- A content system that makes their business show up when AI agents answer questions in their niche\n- Something they can set up once and monitor weekly, not a service they have to manage\n- Clear ROI framing: cost per post, hours saved, citation visibility over time\n- Feels like a tool, not a retainer — they're doers, not delegators\n\n**Trigger event:** They ask ChatGPT about their own niche and a competitor shows up instead. Or they see a competitor's content cited in a Perplexity answer and realize it's a structural advantage, not a writing quality advantage.\n\n## Secondary Pers
